{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_inxs_ver01/data/sn82014519/00414183578/1930122401/0988.xml":{"full_text":"NEW BRITAIN HEIR AT J)\nSecond Section\nPages 11 to 18\nNEW BRITAIN, CONNECTICUT, WEDNESDAY, DECEMBER 24, 1930.\nSHOWNEWPOLICY\nChairman of President's Com\nmittee Points Out Change\n((Copyright, 1930, by United Press.)\nWashington, Dec. 24 (UP) Far\nsighted industrial leaders of the\nUnited States have come to realize\nthe importance of keeping- high\nstandards of wages during periods\nOf depression, Arthur Woods, chair\nroan of President Hoover's emer\ngency committee on unemployment,\nrevealed in an interview with the\nUnited Press.\n\"This change of attitude is one of\nthe most important things about the\npresent situation,\" Woods said.\n\"Business is trying to keep up the\nbuying power of labor. As we go\nInto the new year, that is our most\nhopeful sign.\"\nBusiness leaders. Woods said, are\ntrying something new in economics\nnever before attempted.\n\"In the good old days if we had\nunemployment the business man be\ncame a dictator,\" he said. \"When\nNapoleon had unemployment he\nstarted a war. Until now the proce\ndure has been for every employer\nto batten down his hatches, fire\neveryone he possibly could cut, cut,\ncut.\n\"When he -went to the bank he\nfound he could get no money until\nhe had cut wages and fired rignt\nand left.\nMethod Changes\n\"Now we are doing it differently.\nThe feeling in industry and among\nthe bankers is that it is good busi\nness for them to take care of their\npeople. We are in touch with hun\ndreds of leaders. They are general\nly convinced three things are neces\nsary. \"First, they feel it is good busi\nness to keep people wherever they\ncan instead of firing them indis\ncriminately to get costs down. When\nthe number of work hours must be\nreduced the tendency is to keep the\nexisting unit wage and reduce the\nhours of employes so that all have\nsome work instead of many having\nnone at all.\nHunts for Jobs\n\"Second, instead of shutting down\nthe plant to cut expenses, the mod\nern, business man is looking about\nto see what repairs, replacements\nand other construction ran be wisely\nUndertaken to give jobs.\n\"Third, if an employer must let\nmen go, it is done differently. He\nnow looks into the position of his\nemployes, to see which can best\nweather a period of idleness Some\nhave savings. Single men are laid\neff first. If an employe is turned\nn effort is made to keep in touch\nwith him in a friendly way. Often\nloans without interest are offered, to\nbe paid back when, the man gets\nanother job.\"\nRECEIVER NAMED\nFOR NEWSPAPERS\nMemphis and Knoxrille Publica\ntions Rnn Onto Rocks\nNashville, Tenn., Dec. 24 UP)\nLarkin E. Crouch, Nashville attor\nney, arranged to furnish $25,000\nbond today as receiver for Southern\nPublishers, Inc., holding company\nfor stock of the Memphis Commer\ncial Appeal, Inc., and Knoxville\nJournal. Inc.\nChancellor James B. Newman an\nnounced Dr. Crouch's appointment\nyesterday' when he sustained receiv\nership proceeding instituted by the\nMinnesota and Ontario Paper com\npany, the Nashville Trust company,\ntrustee, and D. D. Robertson, receiv\ner for the Hank of Tennessee.\nChancellor Newman also denied\nan application for a receiver for the\nTennessee Publishing company, pub.\nhshing the Nashville Tennessean and\nlivening Tennessean, saying allega\ntions of mismanagement and dissipa\ntion of assets, denied by the defend\nant, \"do not justify the appointment\nof a receiver of a going concern\nwhose assets are conceded in the\nbill to be greater than its liabilities.\"\nThe Tennessee Publishing Co., suit\nwas brought by the M. and O. Pa\nper company, later joined by the city\nof Asheville, N. C, and receivers for\nthe Central Bank and Trust com\npany of Asheville.\nItalian Specials\nTurin, Dec. 24 (UP) Crown\nPrince Humbert attended the in\nauguration of a Christmas tree at\na school in a Turin suburb. Madon\nna Di Campagua, yesterday. He was\ngreeted warmly by the population.\nPalermo, Dec. 24 (U) The bell\ntower of the church of Santa Maria\nDelia Catena in the commune of\nSanto Stefano Quisqulna was partly\ndemolished when it was struck by\nlightning during a severe storm yes\nterday. The roof of the chapel cav\ned in under the weight of debris,\nand several friars narrowly escaped\ninjury.\nGenoa, Dec. 24 (UP) Harbor\ntraffic decreased only nine per cent\nin the last eleven months, according\nto official statistics published yes\nterday. This figure was said to be\nsmaller than the decrease in most\nAmerican and European ports.\nSpezia, Dec. 24 (UP) Comman\nder Faggioni of the Italian navy and\nthree seamen clung to a buoy in a\nchoppy sea off San Bartolomeo for\nan hour before they were rescued\nMonday night. The motorboat in\nwhich they were cruising capsized\nafter it struck the buoy. The men\nnifXertd from exposure,\nNary Mary Christmas\nIn Merry \"Xmas\" Home\nSuperior, Wis., Dec. 24 UP) It\nwill be a Merry Christmas in the\nChristmas household when Mary\nChristmas and Mrs. Cecil Christ\nmas, William Christmas, her\nfather, said today.\nAnd not only Mary, but Cecil\nChristmas aand Mrs. Cecil Christ\nmas will join mother and father\nChristmas in the Christmas home.\nSo also will Herbert A. Ronn,\nwho last year married Mary\nChristmas, so now there is no\nMary Christmas in the Christmas\nhome except at Christmas.\nBUILDING NEEDS\nFinds More Than $4,500,000,000\nWorth Needed in U. S.\nNew York, Dec. 24 (UP) More\nthan ?4, 500, 000, 000 worth of public\nimprovements are needed in the\nUnited States at the present time\nand cooperation on the part of fed\neral, state and municipal authorities\nin getting this work started would\nfurnish real relief in the unemploy\nment emergency facing the country,\na report issude by S. W. Straus and\nCompany yesterday said.\nBased on reports of 236 leading\nChambers of Commerce throughout\nthe country, the report showed that\nabout $1,200,000,000 of this con\nstruction is now going forward while\napproximately $3,300,000,000 is be\ning held up for various reasons.\nIn New York City alone, $1,300,\n000. 000 of public construction is\nneeded, of which $60o,00ii.0ij0 is go\ning forward at the present time, the\nreport said. Public improvements to\nthe amount of $5Oi.00O.ih') are\nneeded in Chicago, of which only\n$37,000,000 is actually at work.\nIn 172 additional leading cities,\nthe report showed, listed public im\nprovement needs totaled $1,900,000,\n000, of which $485,000,000 is under\nconstruction and $1,415,000,000\npending. In addition, 17 states re\nported they had minimum aggregate\nneeds of $720,000,000, of which 40,\nooo.ooo is going ahead and $680,\n000,000 delayed.\nWETS WILL SEEK\nNEWDISTRICTING\nCochran Says System Is Unfair\nto People\nWashington, Dec. 24 UP) Wets in\ncongress are seeking congressional\nredisricting of every state affected\nby the new apportionment, in tha\nbelief that elections of .-.dditional\nmembers from at large would cheat\nthem of reinforcements.\nRepresentative Cochran, demo\ncrat, of Missouri, said today he\nwould use the house as a forum to\namplify a plea he is preparing to\nmake shortly after congress reas\nsembles. The redistricting must be\ndone by each state.\nRepresentation \"fnfair\"\n\"I mean to put the country on\nnotice,\" Cochran said, \"that the new\nrepresentation will be unfair to the\npopulous centers if the delegations\nare elected at large.\"\nIn each of 22 states which lose\nrepresentation under the new cen\nsus effective with the 73d congress\nthe entire delegation will have to\nbe elected at large unless redis\ntricting is completed in time, like\nwise in 11 states gaining represent\nation. The wets hold that their expected\ngains in rapidly growing cities\nwould be reduced by dry tendencies\nof rural sections which have not\ngained population.\nCochran said 53 per cent of the\npopulation of the country is urban,\nbut 2GS of the 435 representatives\nnow come from rural sections\ndistricts in which a majority of the\nvotes arc In communities of less\nthan 3,000.\nUnlikely to Act\nIt is unlikely congress will act at\nthis session on my aspect of the\nreapportionment question.\nRepresentative Sproul, militant\ndry leader of Kansas, said he had\nno doubt that redistricting will be\ncarried out by the states immedi\nately after March 4.\n\"The drys were asleep.\" Sproul\nadded, \"when they passed the re\napportionment bill. They voted for\nit when they should have opposed\nit. An amendment could have been\neffected to provide enumeration on\nthe basis of citizenship.\"\nCAST IRON DONKEY WILL\nGO TO LOUDEST MEMBER\nTampa Aldermen Presented Willi\nTrophy As Gift For Their\nBest Brayer\nTampa. Fla.. Dec. 24 (VP) Official\nTampa has a holiday problem to\nponder.\nA east iron donkey appeared on\nthe desk of the board of aldermen\nlast night for presentation as a tro\nphy to the \"loudest braying\" mem\nber. The donkey was sent to the board\nthrough Mayor D. B. McKay by\nMrs. Mary J. Burkctt. An accom\npanying letter from the mayor re\nquested \"proper disposition.\" T. N.\nHenderson, board president, said he\nwould name a recipient for the tro\nphy by the next meeting date.\nArgentina leads in grape produc\ntion among Latin-American nations.\nSANTA UNKNOWN\nIN HISOWN CITY\nMoslems Know Little About\nGood Saint Nicholas\nSmyrna, Turkey, Dec. 24 UP.\nSanta Claus virtually is unknown ill\nhis own home town.\nIt was here that Santa, or St.\nNicholas, whose name is different i:i\nnearly every Christian country\nthough his spirit is the same in ail,\nprobably was horn, and it is certain\nthat he was bishop here.\nYet by only a. handful of Amer\nicans and other Christian foreigners\nin Smyrna is St. Nick honored on\nDecember 25. To hundreds of\nthousands of Moslems that day\nbrings no more hope and no more\njoy than any other.\nJust outside Smyrna, in the be\ndraggled little village of Dembre, are\nthe ruins of St. Nicholas' church.\nThere, too, are the ruins of the\nsaint's marble tomb where he was\nburied in 352 A. D. Thousands of\nChristians made pilgrimages to the\ntomb until Italian merchants, 700\nyears after St. Nicholas' death, had\ncarried his body away to Italy.\nPeaants Venerate Tomb\nTo the Moslem peasants, the name\nof St. Nicholas means nothing, but\nthey are sure the tomb was that of\na holy person. They still tie bits of\nrag on the fallen stones in the hope\nof fulfillment of their heart's wishes.\nWhen this little village of Dem\nbre, now crumbling and dirty and\nill-kept, was the great Myra of an\ntiquity, St. Paul visited it. Beyond\nthe village, carved in stone, are the\ntombs of early Christians.\nTo the few Americans and other\nChristian families living in this cor\nner of Asia Minor, Christmas brings\nto life many legends of Santa Claus.\nIt was in and about Smyrna that\nthe fabulous miracles and generous\ndeeds that made St. Nicholas the in\ncarnation of tile Christmas spirit\nof giving are said to have taken\nplace.\nAids Spinster\nOnce, it is related, he dropped\nthree bags of gold stealthily at night\ninto the home of a nobleman whose\nthree lovely daughters could not\ntind husbands because they were\nwithout, dowries. Thus he became\nthe patron saint of spinsters.\nHe is the patron saint of pawn\nbrokers, too, for having converted\na blasphemous pawnbroke of Cala\nbria who smashed the saint's image\nbecause its presence had failed to\nkeep out robbers. When St. Nick\nreformed the robbers as well as th\npawnbroker, the robbers adopted\nhim also.\nSt. Nicholas is credited with re\nstoring to life three schoolboys of\nMyra who had been murdered, thus\nbecoming the beloved patron of\nschool children throughout Christen\ndom. Flashes of Life\nBy the Associated Press.\nSedalia, Mo. Turkey dinners,\ndime each! Fred Kueck served 2,\n227 at his cafe. The fixin's included\ncigars and near beer.\nDenver A $9,000,000 Christmas\ndividend by the Midwest Refining\ncompany is going mostly into one\nexchequer. The Standard Oil com\npany of Indiana owns 99.33 per cent\nof Midwest, which has declared an\nextra dividend of $14 a share.\nOkmuigee, Okla. It cost Joe and\nLucy McUac, wealthy Indians, $8,\n000 to part, but they have been\nhappily reunited for Christmas for\n$7. In successful divorce proceed\nlngs two months ago her attorney\ngot $3,000 and his $5,000. The li\ncense for their remarriage cost $4\nand a justice of the peace perform\ned the ceremony for $3.\nWashington Somebody would\noblige Speaker I.ongworth by giv\ning him a stopwatch. He's lost the\none he uses timing speeches on the\nfloor, or it hua been stolen.\nSea Island Beach, ITa. Mr. and\nran\nw\nr\nIII\nSTATIONERY\nMerry\nChristmas\nHI MAINS! IpJlJjJjJ WE''\nMrs. James J. Tunney are to hunt\nwild turkey during the holidays.\nThey will be Christmas guests of\nMr. and Mrs. Howard E. Ooffin on\nSapelo Island.\nBerlin There are restrictions on\none Christmas color. The govern\nment has forbidden red ink on pos\nters. The idea is that they will be\nless incendiary In some other hue.\nEnglewood, N. J. Baby Lind\nbergh is to visit Grandpa anl\nGrandma Morrow for Christmas. If\nSanta doesn't bring him a plane\neverybody's guess will be vrong.\nCambridge, Mass. Kinctce.i\nscrubwomen discharged by Harvard\nuniversity have received from alum\nni for Christmas amounts ranging\nfrom $69 to $300. The .-t'.te mini\nmum wage commission found the\nwomen were paid two cents an hour\nless than the law required. Th2\nuniversity disagreed.\nWest Talm Beach. Via. -San'a'M\nbrought such a strange thh.g here\nthat all the neighbors have been\ncalling in wonder. Uoren Rowley got\na fine sled. His dad, who has lived\nall his life within earshot of rust\nling palms, was as puzzled as T.oren\nwhat the gift was. Santa got his\norders mixed somehow.\nMuskogee, Okla. Merry Christ\nmas for ick masons over 50 vears\nold from Joe Wheat contractor,\nwho is hising them: \"Old men are\nthe best. They know more, do bet\nter work and do it more easily.\"\nDONEJMRUSSIA\nAlcohol and Communism Don't\nMix, Official Says\nMoscow, Dec. 24 PJ The Soviet\ngovernment, working hand in glove\nwith the Anti-Alcohol society, grad\nually is cutting down Russia's li\nquor supply.\nThe rapidly increasing prices of\nvodka tell the story. The power\nthat, be are trying to make liquor\nhard to get with the idea that ulti\nmately the Soviet republic will be\nwithout an alcoholic taste. The gov\nernment apparently is not concerned\nwith the huge monetary loss it will\nsuffer when the comrades give up\ntheir tippling. Last year, for in\nstance, Russians spent some $750,\no'jo.000 for vodka, beer and wine.\nAs one official views the situation:\n\"Sovietism and alcoholism do not go\ntogether. We must some day have\na liquorless country. When that will\nbe, it is hard to say. Like some of\nour other ideals, it may be difficult\nto attain. But some time it will be\na reality. We do not intend to en\nforce prohibition. We hope to suc\nceed by education and by gradually\ncutting down the supply of alcoholic\nbeverages. We envision a day when\nthere will not even be beer in the\nrepublic.\"\n1'rom the standpoint of the for\neigner visiting Russia, there is not a\ndecent drink in the country today.\nOn his first few hours in Russia, tho\nordinary tourist experiments with a\nshot of vodka. Once, but not twice.\nHe almost immediately \"goes on the\nwagon.\" For vodka, to the uninitiat\ned, is chain lightning. It is also bit\nter and most unappetizing. The beer\nis also scarce and not good. The\nwine is a little better, but still far\nfrom being a nector of the gods.\nAt present there are no saloons or\ncabarets, nightclubs or speakeasies\nin Russia. Mild beer can be had\nonly in state-owned hotels and res\ntaurants and in the sarious union\nclubs.\nPHELPS BOOSTS YALE\nAugusta, Ga., Dec. 24 OP) Dr.\nWilliam Lyon Phelps, Yale profes\nsor, commenting on Dr. Nicholas\nMurray Butler's suggestion for an\n\"athletic league of nations\" said:\n\"Until Yale has succeeded in beating\nHarvard and the University of\nGeorgia under perfect conditions I\nshould not like to see any change.\"\nA German airplane builder is ex\nperimenting with a low-wing mono\nplane having stabilizers at the ends\nof the wing to prevent spins.\nROCKNE MUST QUIT\nSTRENUOUSCAREER\nNotre Dame Coach Will Forego\nOutside Activities\nChicago, Dec. 24 UP) The Knutu\nRockne of 1930, \"a man with a\nthousand duties,\" is a figure of the\npast.\nThat was the consensus of the\nfamous Notre Dame football coach s\nclosest friends today after reading\nthe advice of his physician to quit\n\"the too strenuous life.\"\nJust how far Rockne would go to\nappease the worry of his family,\nphysician and friends was a matter\nof divided personal opinion. Many\nbelieved he would retire from active\neoaching and become director of\nathletics at Notre Dame. Some\ngussed he would take a year's leave\nof absence, while the majority were\nquite certain he would merely re\nfrain from his many extra activities\nand devote all his time and atten\ntion to Notre Dame football.\nThe latter belief appeared most\ncorrect. On his return from the\nNotre Dame-Southern California\nfootball game December 10, Rockne\ntold the Associated Press that he\nplanned to \"stop writing, speaking\nNow\nLet\n'Very\nThe Fair\nDavidson Leventhal\nover radio and to luncheon clubs\nand all the extras that I have been\ntrying to handle.\"\n\"All this extra activity, along with\nthe natural worries a football coach\nhas to\" contend with, has me fa\ntigued,\" ho said. \"I've got to stop\nit or. it's all going to stop me.\"\nBOTTOMJNJUROPE\nAssistant Secretary of Com\nmerce Reports On Trade\nNew York, Dec. '24 (UP) Unem\nployment in Kurope will reach its\npeak toward the latter part of Janu\nary, when 7,500,000 persons are ex\npected to be out of work. Dr. Julian\nKlein, assistant secretary of com\nmerce, predicts after spending sev\neral months studying conditions\nabroad.\nDr. Klein, who returned on the\nLeviathan, said France, which has\nso far been lightly affected by the\ncurrent depression, is beginning to\nfeel it now.\n\"The economic conditions are re\nsponsible for the political disturb\nances.\" Dr. Klein said. \"Some pre\ndicted it, some arc on now, and\nIs The\nFOR ALL GOOD MEN AND TRUE1\nTO PREPARE THEIR PARTS\nAND KEEP SET THE STAGE\nFOR THE\nWORLD'S PREMIER PRESENTATION\nTHE PROSPECTS OF I93f\nMay it be a comedy, not\nfarcical, but one which has\nhanolness and brightness for\nits theme, wherein there is\nmuch whole-hearted laughter\nand an abundant joy of life\npredominates each scene.\nAS WE ALL HAVE A ROLE TO\nIt is well that our mental make-up be\ncorrect and in tune with the plot, so as\nnot to mar the piece or prevent its near\nattainment to perfection.\nThe ordeals of 1930 must\ntherefore be forgotten. Look\ning ahead with confidence\nto better things will improve\nour attitude and perspective\nand create a determination\nto make the play a success.\nUs All Strain Every Effort to Put the Show\nOver, So that Critics in Review Will Say:\n\"A Brilliant, Joyful Affair Indeed, a Striking\nDepartune From its Predecessor\"\nSWerry Christmas\nsome will come later.\"\nNot AU Chaos\n\"I don't want to give the impres\nsion,\" he said, \"that everything in\nKurope is in a state of chaos. Ex\nports are-off quite a lot, but our ex\nporters should realize that even now\nthere are openings to be found. In\nventories all over Europe are deplet\ned. There is a desire to buy, but\nthere is a lack of actual money.\"\nSilas H. Strawn, vice chairman of\nthe International Chamber of Com\nmerce, who returned from a meet\ning in Paris, said in a prepared\nstatement:\n\"Everyone at the conference real\nized the menace to world trade\ncaused by the activities of the Rus\nsians in forcing upon the world\nlarge quantities of grain and raw\nmaterials.\"\nUnemployment, he said, is forcing\nmanufacturers to extend more credit\nto Russia for raw materials and ma\nchinery. \"No one knows the Soviets'\nability to pay.\"\nSons of Italy Shower\nPresents On Children\nWidows and children of members\nof the Sons of Italy gathered at the\nclub rooms on Walnut street last\nnight to enjoy the first annual\nChristmas tree to, be given hf the\nclub in the club rooms. Frank Ce\ncere was the Santa Claus.\nThe children received gifts and\nrefreshments were served.\nTime\nREDISCOUNT RATE\nLOWESTIN WORLD\nTwo Per Cent Figure Goes Into\nEffect Today\nNew York, Dec. 24 CP) A redis\ncount rate of 2 per cent the low\nest in the history of the federal re\nserve system and the lowest in the\nworld went into effect in the New\nYork Federal Reserve bank today.\nThe announcement that the rate\nat which member banks might bor\nrow had been cut from 2 1-2 per\ncent was construed by newspapers as\na stimulus to business revival and a\nmark of confidence in the nation's\ncondition.\nBankers were oupted as saying\nthat the federal reserve's action in\ninviting member banks to avail\nthemselves freely of its credit was\nthe most constructive move possible,\nin view of the widespread disturb\nances in the banking field.\nIn addition. Wall street opined.\nthe reduction would renew faith\nabroad in the strength of the New\nYork money market. If the closing\nof two banks here had created dis\ntrust in the financial center, it w\nsaid, the' federal reserve directors\nwould have taken a different step.\nPLAY","height":"25804","width":"19196"}}
